## PART V — THE HARDWARE VISION

### The Central Claim

Every other AI system separates the hardware from the intelligence. The chip runs the model. In Mashet's hardware embodiment: **the chip is the intelligence.** The substrate graph is not loaded onto the chip. The substrate graph IS the chip. The topology of the silicon is the topology of the reasoning.

### ASIC Architecture

**Substrate Node Processing Units (SNPUs):** Each substrate node is physically instantiated as a dedicated condition-evaluation processing unit in silicon. The SNPU receives signals from prerequisite SNPUs, evaluates whether all conditions are satisfied, activates if they are, and emits signals on all outgoing connections.

**Variable-Conductance Inter-Node Connections (VCICs):** Each directed edge is physically instantiated as a variable-conductance connection between SNPUs. Conductance corresponds to edge weight. Edge type is encoded in the connection's signal routing logic.

**The Von Neumann Elimination:** In the Mashet ASIC, the substrate graph topology is the program. The SNPU activation state is the memory. Signal propagation through VCICs is the processing. All three functions are unified in one physical structure. The von Neumann separation between processor, memory, and program — which has defined computing architecture since 1945 — is eliminated.

**Dynamic Edge Addition:** The ASIC implements a programmable interconnect fabric that allows Loop 4 to add new edges (activate new VCICs) as the substrate graph grows. This means the chip's physical connection topology evolves through use — a capability without precedent in commercial silicon.

**Fabrication pathway:** FPGA prototype → ASIC tape-out → licensing to fab partners (ARM model). The architecture is patentable, its hardware claims are novel, and there is no equivalent prior art in the neuromorphic chip space because neuromorphic chips (Intel Loihi, IBM NorthPole) implement weighted neural architectures, not typed symbolic substrate traversal.

